  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying regulatory authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal AML policies\n- Training employees on detection\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Legal Regulations\n- Complying with Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Following Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering standards\n\n5. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Preserving documentation for specified periods\n- Ensuring data is accessible for potential investigations\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant financial penalties, potential criminal charges, and loss of operational licenses.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific obligations?",
